{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510473"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:30:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:30:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11567"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11567"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.66,0.16,0.01,0.15,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4196"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101656"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4196"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11567"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84099"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1628"},{"type":"tags","id":"4546"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"10948"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6382"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8365"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26981"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33918"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35256"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44680"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101656"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman and her 35-year-old partner present to the General Practice clinic after trying to conceive for 18 months without success. She began menstruating at age 15 and reports regular 35-day cycles, with periods lasting approximately six days. She has never been pregnant. She has no history of sexually transmitted infections, and her cervical screening tests are up to date and normal. Her medical history includes mild depression managed with counselling. Her body mass index is 32 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. She does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer partner previously fathered a pregnancy that ended in termination in another relationship. He had chlamydia at age 23, treated with azithromycin. He is an active smoker with a body mass index of 29 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth drink one to two standard drinks a few times a week. The couple have regular unprotected vaginal intercourse and have attempted to time intercourse with ovulation. They were previously advised to optimise their lifestyle and continue trying to conceive, but have now returned after a further eight months without success. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in investigating this woman\u0027s infertility?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ovarian reserve and ovulatory function testing","Mid-luteal oestrogen","Endometrial biopsy","Hysterosalpingography ultrasound","Oocyte evaluation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor a couple who have been unable to conceive after more than 12 months of regular unprotected intercourse, it is appropriate to begin investigations for infertility. The recommended \u003Cstrong\u003Eovarian reserve and ovulatory function testing\u003C/strong\u003E includes day 2-4 follicle-stimulating hormone, estradiol, and anti-mullerian hormone, and mid-luteal progesterone. Elevated estradiol, elevated FSH or reduced anti-mullerian hormone may be indicative of diminished ovarian reserve. A progesterone level approximately 7 days before menstruation is a very useful marker of ovulatory function, particularly in patients with inter-cycle variation. These are considered first-line investigations for a woman with regular cycles and no obvious cause of infertility in the history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMid-luteal oestrogen\u003C/strong\u003E is not a reliable marker of ovulation; mid-luteal progesterone is preferred for confirming ovulatory cycles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometrial biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely indicated in the initial work-up of infertility and is reserved for specific indications such as suspected endometrial pathology or recurrent pregnancy loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHysterosalpingography ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for assessing tubal patency and uterine structure, but is generally performed after initial hormonal and ovulatory assessment unless there is a high suspicion of tubal disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOocyte evaluation\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard first-line investigation and is typically considered only in the context of assisted reproductive technologies such as in vitro fertilisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is also important to consider semen analysis early in the assessment, as male factors accounts for 20-50% of infertility presentations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First-line investigations for infertility in a woman include assessment of ovarian reserve and ovulatory function.","Ovarian reserve is best evaluated with day 2-4 follicle-stimulating hormone, oestradiol, and anti-mullerian hormone.","Semen analysis should be considered early in the work-up of a couple with primary infertility."],"references":["Hunt S, Vollenhoven B. Assessment of female fertility in the general practice setting. Aust J Gen Pract. 2020 Jun;49(6):304-308. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-01-20-5205. PMID: 32464730. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32464730/","National Institute for Health and Care Excellence. Fertility problems: assessment and management. [Internet]. [London]: NICE; 2013 [updated 2017 Sep; cited 2025 Jan 12]. (Clinical guideline [CG156]). https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg156","Infertility Workup for the Women\u0027s Health Specialist: ACOG Committee Opinion, Number 781. Obstet Gynecol. 2019 Jun;133(6):e377-e384. doi: 10.1097/AOG.0000000000003271. PMID: 31135764. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31135764/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84099"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11567"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84099"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-03T18:09:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-07T10:15:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4196"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101656"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","n